	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />VCC / VEE is typically used on circuits involving bipolar transistors. VCC means "Voltage Collector", and VEE "Voltage Emmiter". VEE can either be equal to GND (0V) or be a negative voltage, so use of numbered voltage is defintely better.
<br />
<br />VDD / VSS is typically used on circtits involving FET transistors. VDD is "Voltage Drain" and VSS "Voltage Source".
<br />Since FET transistors are more recent, normally VDD and VSS should be newer than VCC and VEE. However, I'm unsure, and the use of numbered voltage can be better (+5V is more meaningfull than VCC or VDD).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


